notesStmt.note: This late twelfth- or early thirteenth-century Psalter was made for a female supplicant, and is of Premonstratensian use. Created and used in Rhineland, Germany, it remained there until the French Revolution, after which it was eventually acquired by the English book collector Sir Thomas Phillipps. The Psalter is liturgical, and therefore has eight divisions for the liturgical week, as well as the usual tripartite divisions. Each of these major psalms is marked by large lively inhabited or foliate initials. Early added prayers on the first and last blank pages, as well as occasional marginal prayers and notes in a variety of hands, attest to the manuscript's use through time.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is Latin.

msItem.title: Psalter
msItem.note: Psalter and prayers for a female supplicant

msItem.title: Prayer to the Virgin
msItem.rubric: Oratio bona et utilis de beata virgine.
msItem.note: Text is later addition, written in late thirteenth-century hand

msItem.title: Liturgical Psalter
msItem.note: Divisions at eight psalms for the liturgical week (Psalms 1, 26, 38, 52, 68, 80, 97, and 109), with additional divisions at Psalms 51 and 101 (these comprise the usual tripartite division that includes Psalm 1); each psalm ends with a verse of a Psalterium Beatae Mariae; charm added fol. 20r under Psalm 21: "Grabbatim zephap pantazer primellus/Adiutor meus esto domino fac quod peto ne/moreris"; Psalms 148 and 149 conflated

msItem.title: Litany, petitions, and collects
msItem.incipit: Domine ihesu christe filii dei vivi
msItem.note: Litany contains twenty-four martyrs, seventeen confessors, twelve virgins (including Genovefa); texts are as follows: fol. 179r: Collect; fols. 179v-180v: Litany; fols. 181r-182r: petitions; fols. 182r-184r: Preces and collects

msItem.title: Collects, prayers, hymns, creeds, Gospel sequence
msItem.note: The last four pages, fols. 199-202, have had their outer, and in one case also lower, margins cut off, but the textblocks are intact; texts are as follows: fol. 189v: Three collects; fols. 190r-193r: Seven prayers to the Trinity; fol. 193r: Hymn; fols. 193r-194r: Creeds; fols. 194r-198r: Ten prayers to the Trinity, with antiphons; fol. 198r: Antiphon for St. Martin; fol. 198r: Responsory and versicle for St. John; fol. 198r-v: Two prayers; fols. 198v-199v: Hymn to the Trinity; fols. 199v-200r: Gospel sequence, St. John; fols. 200v-201r: Two prayers with an antiphon; fol. 201r: Collect; fols. 201v-202r: De sancta anima domini; fol. 202r: Added prayer, nearly contemporary with manuscript, probably late twelfth or early thirteenth century

msItem.title: Added prayer
msItem.incipit: Pater de caelis deus qui nusisti filium tuum
msItem.note: Prayer added to blank page, possibly second quarter of the thirteenth century

support.p: Somewhat yellowed parchment; uneven weight, ranging from thin to thick

supportDesc.foliation: Modern pencil foliation, upper right corners rectos

handDesc.handNote: Pre-Gothic formal bookhand; two sizes of script in Office of the Dead (fols. 184r-192r)

decoDesc.decoNote: Large initials mark psalm divisions: inhabited initials fols. 1v, 25v, 41r, 55v, 56v, 72r, and 110v; historiated initial fol. 126r; foliate initials fols. 90v and 108r

Seven inhabited and two historiated initials with beasts and human figures (7-15 lines); two foliate initials (9-10 lines); initials drawn in black and red pen, often with gold or yellow wash backgrounds and red and green accents; Psalms begin with red pen-drawn decorative initials with blue or green flourishes (3-8 lines); Psalm verses begin with red initials (1 line high); rubrics in red, text in black ink

decoNote.title: Initial "Q" with man battling dragon (Quid gloriaris)
Initial "S" with man battling dragon (Salvum me)
Initial "D" with God the Father and God the Son (?) (Dixit dominus)
Initial "C" with bust of Isaiah (?) (Confitebor tibi)

binding.p: Sixteenth-century German beech boards, originally covered in brown leather; re-covered in green velvet in the nineteenth century by Léon Gruel, Paris; clasp and catch plates are sixteenth century, poorly refitted

history.provenance: Made for Premonstratensian use (Office of the Dead is of this use), or possibly also Augustinian use (two mentions of Augustine in litany and multiple prayers to the Trinity), probably in Rhineland (litany includes Mosan saints), late twelfth or early thirteenth century
Owned by Rhenish abbeys before French Revolution
Leander van Ess of Darmstadt, acquired from Rhenish abbeys after French Revolution
Sir Thomas Phillipps, 1824, by purchase, no. 441; Ex-libris fol. 1r: rampant lion stamp and inscription "Sir T.P./Middle Hill 441"
Phillipps's sale, London (either 1911, no. 868, or 1913, no. 1021)
Henry Walters, Baltimore, acquired from Gruel before 1931
history.acquisition: Walters Art Museum, 1931, by Henry Walters' bequest
